JSP : Java Server Page
Advantages:
 i)Extension to the servlet
 ii)Easy to maintain
 iii)Fast development: No need to recompile and redeploy
 iv)Less code than servlet
 
 
 JSP Lifecycle:
 
 i)Tanslation of JSP page
 ii)Compilation of JSP page
 iii)Classloading
 iv)Instantiation(Object creation)
 v)Initialization(container invokes jspinit())
 vi)Request Processing(container invokes _jspService())
 vii)Destroy(container invokes jspDestroy())
 
 Container : Server
 
 Jsp : @ Directive
 
 Tags:
 i)Scriplet Tag   <%  code %>
 ii)Expression Tag <%= code %> 
 iii)Declaration Tag <%! code %>
 
 
 Implicit Object:
 i)Request
 ii)Response
 iii)Config
 iv)Application
 v)Session
 vi)PageContext
    Scopes: page, request, session, application
 vii)Page(Object)
 viii)Exception
 
 Error Page: 404
 
 
 
 Directives:
 i)Page  : <%@ page attribute="value" %>
 ii)Include
 iii)Taglib
 
 Web Application: Multiple page
 
 Action Tags:
 These are special types of tags used to perform specific tasks.
 
 i)jsp:forward : It forwards the request and response from one resource to another resource.
 ii)jsp:include : It includes a resource in the current page.
 iii)jsp:useBean : Creates a bean object.
 iv)jsp:setProperty :sets the value of property in bean object
 v)jsp:getProperty : displays the value property of the bean object.
 vi)jsp:param : It sets parameter value.
 vii)jsp:fallback: Displays a message if plugin is not working.
 viii)jsp:plugin : Embed another resource.(ex: applet, bean) 
 
 Bean - Java class
 
 
 
 
 
 